{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657425"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:28:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:28:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19589"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19589"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.25,0.19,0.13,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12360"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85949"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12360"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19589"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70208"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29442"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29448"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29489"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85949"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe oesophageal hiatus is an important anatomical landmark in the diaphragm. During surgical procedures in this region, such as para-oesophageal hernia repair, careful attention must be paid to nearby vascular structures. The image shows a surgically widened hiatus (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://emedici.com/storage/media/1b2104b2-5485-4eb3-8ad3-672b02ab136f.jpg\u0022\u003EImage\u003C/a\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the vascular structure indicated by the arrow?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inferior phrenic vein","Inferior epigastric vein","Superior epigastric vein","Short gastric vein","Left gastric vein"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe structure indicated is the \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior phrenic vein\u003C/strong\u003E, which drains blood from the diaphragm and typically empties into either the inferior vena cava or left renal vein. These vessels course along the inferior surface of the diaphragm and are particularly vulnerable during hiatal surgery. The inferior phrenic veins are paired structures that accompany the inferior phrenic arteries and are important in maintaining diaphragmatic circulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInferior epigastric vein\u003C/strong\u003E courses within the anterior abdominal wall, posterior to the rectus abdominis muscle. It begins near the umbilicus and ascends to join the external iliac vein. This vessel is not found near the oesophageal hiatus.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior epigastric vein\u003C/strong\u003E is found in the anterior abdominal wall as a continuation of the internal thoracic vein. It descends behind the rectus abdominis muscle and anastomoses with the inferior epigastric vein. Its location is far anterior to the hiatus.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShort gastric vein\u003C/strong\u003E connects the greater curvature of the stomach to the splenic vein. These are multiple small vessels in the gastrosplenic ligament that drain the fundus of the stomach. They are located lateral to the hiatus.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft gastric vein\u003C/strong\u003E drains the lesser curvature of the stomach into the portal vein. While it passes near the oesophageal hiatus, it follows a different course and is typically larger than the vessel shown.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the location of the inferior phrenic vessels is crucial during hiatal surgery to prevent inadvertent injury and bleeding complications. These vessels can be particularly problematic if injured during dissection as they may retract into the diaphragm, making haemostasis difficult to achieve. The inferior phrenic vessels also provide collateral circulation in cases of coeliac axis stenosis and can become enlarged in hepatocellular carcinoma, making their identification even more important.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The inferior phrenic veins drain the diaphragm and typically empty into either the inferior vena cava or left renal vein.","The inferior phrenic vessels run in close proximity to the oesophageal hiatus and are at risk during hiatal surgery.","The inferior phrenic arteries have variable origins including the aorta, coeliac axis, or renal arteries."],"references":["Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70208"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19589"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21632"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21632"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/KYdEblRyZiu68QzETJ6cOuzEBp7nCF.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/KYdEblRyZiu68QzETJ6cOuzEBp7nCF.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":572,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70208"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-18T17:49:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02